{"title_page": "Arcadia Fund", "text_new": "{{Advert|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = Arcadia Fund\n| logo = Arcadia Fund Logo.png\n| formation = {{start date and age|2001}}<ref name=\":3\"/>\n| founders = {{unbulleted list|[[Peter Baldwin (professor)|Peter Baldwin]]|[[Lisbet Rausing]]}}\n| purpose = Preserve Endangered Cultural Heritage and Ecosystems, Promoting Open Access\n| headquarters = [[London, England]], UK\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| owner = \n| key_people = <nowiki>Professor Peter Baldwin</nowiki>{{small|(Trustee)}}<br>Lisbet Rausing {{small|(Trustee)}}<br>[[Dr Johannes Burger]] {{small|(Trustee)}}<br>\n| revenue = \n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.arcadiafund.org.uk/|}}\n| num_employees = 9\n| Advisory Board = 7 Members\n}}\n\nThe '''Arcadia Fund''' is a UK charity organisation founded by [[Lisbet Rausing]] and Professor [[Peter Baldwin (professor)|Peter Baldwin]]. Established in 2001, the organisation provides grants on a worldwide basis. Its primary focus currently is preserving endangered culture, preserving endangered nature and providing open access.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.foundationguide.org/foundations-trust/arcadia-fund/|title=Arcadia Fund|last=foundationguide|website=Foundation Guide|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>  <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arcadiafund.org.uk/about-peter-baldwin-lisbet-rausing/|title=About us - preserving endangered culture and nature and promoting open access|website=Arcadia Fund|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-08}}</ref>\n\nSince 2002, the fund has provided in excess of $570 million in projects around the world.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arcadiafund.org.uk/|title=Arcadia - preserve endangered culture and nature|website=Arcadia Fund|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\nThe foundation is controlled by its three trustees ([[Lisbet Rausing]], [[Peter Baldwin (professor)|Peter Baldwin]] and Dr Johannes Burger) and its team of 9 members. The fund also has an advisory board of 7 members.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arcadiafund.org.uk/about-peter-baldwin-lisbet-rausing/people/|title=People - The Arcadia team|website=Arcadia Fund|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nArcadia has since 2002 provided in excess of $570 million globally in Grants.<ref name=\":3\" /> The grants are divided into 5 categories: Cultural, Environmental, Open Access, Discretionary and Discontinued Themes as shown in the following table  <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://data.threesixtygiving.org/|title=Data Registry {{!}} 360Giving|website=data.threesixtygiving.org|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Type Of Grant\n!Grant Total ($USD)\n!Percentage of Total Grants\n|-\n|Cultural\n|204,585,494\n|41%\n|-\n|Environmental\n|183,564,272\n|37%\n|-\n|Open Access\n|29,922,879\n|6%\n|-\n|Discretionary\n|40,403,816\n|8%\n|-\n|Discontinued Themes\n|34,317,384\n|7%\n|}\n\n\nArcadia's supported causes since inception in 2002 have been preserving endangered culture, preserving endangered nature and open access. Arcadia's has a selected issues criterion in which the organisation use's to choose grants. The methodology of grant choices has not changed since 2002 however, supported causes has altered slightly. Arcadia aims to provide cultural grants to universities, archives or museums that preserve cultural heritage and digitise near-extinct cultural heritage. Additionally, Arcadia provides environmental grants to organisations that preserve endangered habitats, at risk land as well as trains staff, enable research and policy development. Arcadia also aims to provide open access grants to increase access of free material such online as research papers and publications.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nArcadia also supported causes such as human rights, philanthropy and education however since 2009 the support for the causes have been discontinued.<ref name=\":1\" />  The fund supported organisations around these discontinued themes that helped refugee scholars, educated disadvantaged children in Africa, and conducted women's right advocacy.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe Graph shows the fund's grants per years<ref name=\":2\" /><graph>{\n\t\"version\": 2,\n\t\"width\": 400,\n\t\"height\": 200,\n\t\"data\": [\n\t\t{\n\t\t\t\"name\": \"table\",\n\t\t\t\"values\": [\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2002,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 46067813\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2003,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 5000000\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2004,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 26967408\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2005,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 14372529\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2006,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 22616179\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2007,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 12784924\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2008,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 23391519\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2009,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 28692782\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2010,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 6092000\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2011,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 82048811\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2012,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 12825619\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2013,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 14663180\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2014,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 30722939\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2015,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 6722749\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2016,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 37216842\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2017,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 86579402\n\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t{\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": 2018,\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": 36029151\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t]\n\t\t}\n\t],\n\t\"scales\": [\n\t\t{\n\t\t\t\"name\": \"x\",\n\t\t\t\"type\": \"linear\",\n\t\t\t\"range\": \"width\",\n\t\t\t\"zero\": false,\n\t\t\t\"domain\": {\n\t\t\t\t\"data\": \"table\",\n\t\t\t\t\"field\": \"x\"\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t},\n\t\t{\n\t\t\t\"name\": \"y\",\n\t\t\t\"type\": \"linear\",\n\t\t\t\"range\": \"height\",\n\t\t\t\"nice\": true,\n\t\t\t\"domain\": {\n\t\t\t\t\"data\": \"table\",\n\t\t\t\t\"field\": \"y\"\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t],\n\t\"axes\": [\n\t\t{\n\t\t\t\"type\": \"x\",\n\t\t\t\"scale\": \"x\"\n\t\t},\n\t\t{\n\t\t\t\"type\": \"y\",\n\t\t\t\"scale\": \"y\"\n\t\t}\n\t],\n\t\"marks\": [\n\t\t{\n\t\t\t\"type\": \"area\",\n\t\t\t\"from\": {\n\t\t\t\t\"data\": \"table\"\n\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\"properties\": {\n\t\t\t\t\"enter\": {\n\t\t\t\t\t\"x\": {\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"scale\": \"x\",\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"field\": \"x\"\n\t\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y\": {\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"scale\": \"y\",\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"field\": \"y\"\n\t\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t\t\"y2\": {\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"scale\": \"y\",\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"value\": 0\n\t\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t\t\"fill\": {\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"value\": \"steelblue\"\n\t\t\t\t\t},\n\t\t\t\t\t\"interpolate\": {\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\"value\": \"monotone\"\n\t\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t]\n}</graph>\n<br />\n\n== Activities ==\nArcadia awards grants to organisations preserving endangered culture, preserving nature, and promoting open access.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arcadiafund.org.uk/grants/|title=Grants - dynamic, sustainable and well researched programmes|website=Arcadia Fund|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Culture ===\nArcadia's largest grant was in 2002, to the [[SOAS, University of London|School of Oriental and African Studies]]\u2014 totalling \u00a320 million (US$33,851,813) to start the [[Endangered Languages Archive|Endangered Language Documentation Program (ELDP)]]. The program enables scholars to undertake documentation of disappearing languages. By 2015, the program has documented over 350 languages. The grant also funds training scholars in modern language documentation techniques. The fund   donated another US$11 million in April 2015 .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.soas.ac.uk/news/newsitem102002.html|title=SOAS\u2019 Endangered Languages Documentation Programme receives a further $11 million from Arcadia {{!}} SOAS University of London|website=www.soas.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>\n\nIn  2004 the fund founded the Endangered Archives Program at the [[British Library]] with a $25 million grant supporting the digitisation of at risk collections around the world. By Sept 2018,  the program has supported more than 350 documentation programs in 90 countries, with over 6.5 million images and 25,000 sound tracks being preserved. The material is available freely online as part of the [[Endangered Archives Programme]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eap.bl.uk/|title=Endangered Archives Programme|website=Endangered Archives Programme|language=en|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref> In 2018 the fund gave an additional  \u00a39 million to fund the program for a further 7 years. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arcadiafund.org.uk/new-grant-to-the-endangered-archives-programme/|title=New grant to the Endangered Archives Programme|date=2018-09-25|website=Arcadia Fund|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 and 2015 provide  $1 million  to the [[Smithsonian Institution]]'s collaboration with the [[National Museum of Natural History|Natural History Museum]]'s \"Recovering Voices Initiative,\"  a long-term project  to digitise audio recordings, manuscripts and photographs. It aims to digitise the entire collection of ethnographic sound recordings, estimated at 3,000 hours, and 35,000 pages of manuscript materials.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://smithsoniancampaign.org/campaign-update/arcadia-fund-gift-furthers-global-access-endangered-languages|title=Arcadia Fund Gift Furthers Global Access to Endangered Languages|website=smithsoniancampaign.org|language=en|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref> In 2015 it  provided a $511,200 to the Smithsonian Campaign, 'The Field Book Project', to preserve field books, the  original records of scientific expeditions.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://siarchives.si.edu/about/field-book-project|title=Field Book Project|last=KapsalisE|date=2017-01-27|website=Smithsonian Institution Archives|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>   The grant aimed to support the digitising of 2600 field books, all which will be open access.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.biodiversitylibrary.org/2015/08/the-arcadia-fund-awards-grant-to-support-the-field-book-project.html|title=The Arcadia Fund Awards Grant to Support The Field Book Project \u2013 Biodiversity Heritage Library|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref> Currently, the project has catalogued over 9,500 field books and digitised over 4,000.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== Environment ===\nArcadia in 2018 gave \u00a323 million (US$31,441,100)   to the Cambridge Conservative Initiative (CCI) for the Endangered Landscapes Programme (ELP). Arcadia in collaboration with CCI and 9 other conservation organisations aim to reserve priority landscape across Europe  to support viable populations of native species, provide room for natural ecological processes, resilience of ecosystems to short or long term changes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cam.ac.uk/research/news/restoring-europes-endangered-landscapes-for-life|title=Restoring Europe\u2019s endangered landscapes for life|date=2018-10-09|website=University of Cambridge|language=en|access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref> \n\nArcadia in 2018 gave Fauna & Flora International   $USD 27,000,000 for Halcyon Land & Sea Fund. The partnership started in 1998 where Peter Baldwin and Lisbet Rausing developed the idea in conjunction with FFI to develop the Halcyon Fund in which secures highly threatened sites to protect them under local management. As of 2018, the fund has supported 46 projects in 25 countries, protecting 55.8 million hectares of habitat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fauna-flora.org/news/major-grant-arcadia-will-help-ffi-manage-vital-areas-conservation|title=Major grant from Arcadia will help FFI manage vital areas for conservation {{!}} Fauna & Flora International|website=www.fauna-flora.org|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref> Since 2011, the fund has provided support in which has supported 34 initiatives across 18 countries.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fauna-flora.org/news/tracking-wolves-and-tracking-progress|title=Tracking wolves and tracking progress {{!}} Fauna & Flora International|website=www.fauna-flora.org|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref> Currently, Arcadia's total funding to FFI is $USD 51,550,000 million.<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2015, Arcadia ordered an independent expert review of the work it had funded through FFI, which  stated that, \"The report clearly recognises the invaluable role that Arcadia has played in helping FFI evolve into the organisation it is today, by providing long-term and flexible funding for a considerable and effective body of work.\".<ref name=\":4\" /> Its first grant in 2011 for the Halcyon Marine Programme has led to a programme in 72 sites in 17 countries withr 88 partners and 35 community-based institutions and has already resulted in threat reduction of biodiversity recovery at 10 sites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arcadiafund.org.uk/fauna-flora-international/|title=Fauna & Flora International|date=2017-01-26|website=Arcadia Fund|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Open Access ===\nArcadia has provided multiple grants to Harvard University  to improve open access at the university. In 2009 it awarded  $5 million over a 5-year period.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2009/04/harvard-university-library-awarded-5m-grant-from-arcadia-fund/|title=Harvard University Library awarded $5M grant from Arcadia Fund|date=2009-04-09|website=Harvard Gazette|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> The grant wil  support the processing of 17th and 18th century collections in archives and underwrite conservation treatments of fragile or damaged 17th or 18th century collections. It will also help to catalogue and digitise documents on Harvard's history, and to run the Library Lab programme to improve digital services .<ref name=\":2\" /> I Arcadia provided further support to the university in 2011 with an additional $11 million grant.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn September 2015, the fund gave $450,000 over 3 years to [[Creative Commons]]. to develop tools that complement current CC licence suite.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://creativecommons.org/2015/09/25/creative-commons-awarded-450000-from-the-arcadia-fund-to-support-open-access-publishing-for-authors/|title=Creative Commons awarded $450,000 from the Arcadia Fund to support open access publishing for authors|date=2015-09-25|website=Creative Commons|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, the fund gave $5 million to the [[Wikimedia Foundation]], the largest contribution to the foundation at the time.   <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.wikimedia.org/2017/09/25/wikimedia-endowment-matching-gift/|title=Matching gift grows Wikimedia Endowment by $10 million \u2013 Wikimedia Blog|language=en|access-date=2019-05-04}}</ref> It gave another $3.5 million   in 2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wikimediafoundation.org/2019/04/24/peter-baldwin-lisbet-rausing-give-an-additional-3-5-million-to-the-wikimedia-endowment/|title=Peter Baldwin, Lisbet Rausing give an additional $3.5 million to the Wikimedia Endowment|date=2019-04-24|website=Wikimedia Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-04}}</ref>\n\n=== Discretionary ===\nThe Arcadia Fund in 2015 gave $25 million to [[Yale University]] to renovate the Yale Hall of Graduates Studies enabling the university to co-locate the dispersed humanities departments to under one roof. offering a setting for cross-disciplinary collaboration and advance research. .<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.yale.edu/2015/03/25/gift-transform-hall-graduate-studies-honors-david-swensen|title=Gift to transform Hall of Graduate Studies honors David Swensen|date=2015-03-25|website=YaleNews|language=en|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref> Baldwin and Rausing have asked in tribute to the service of [[David F. Swensen|David Swensen]] (Who built Yale's endowment from $1.3 billion to $23.9 billion) that the building should be named after him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pionline.com/article/20150406/PRINT/304069991/yale-to-name-building-after-swensen|title=Yale to name building after Swensen|last=Comtois|first=James|last2=Comtois|first2=James|date=2015-04-06|website=Pensions & Investments|language=en|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref>\n\nArcadia gave \u00a35 million to the illuminated River Foundation in 2017 <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theartnewspaper.com/news/illuminated-river-project-gets-off-the-ground-with-four-bridges-lit-on-the-thames-next-year|title=Multi-million pound donation gives Illuminated River project the green light for next year|website=theartnewspaper.com|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>towards its program for a commissioned art installation of light to 15 of Central London's bridges along the River Thames. When the project is completed it would be the longest art commission in the world at 2.5 miles long.  ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arcadiafund.org.uk/the-illuminated-river-foundation/|title=The Illuminated River Foundation|date=2018-10-08|website=Arcadia Fund|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>  {{Cite web|url=https://thedeveloper.live/places/places/london-is-only-here-because-of-the-thames|title=Illuminated River|website=The Developer|language=En|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Discontinued Themes ===\nThe fund before 2009 were involved in supporting  human rights,  supporting organisations to help refugee scholars, educate disadvantaged children in Africa, and conduct women's right advocacy. In 2005, it provided a $5 million grant to the Mvule Trust, to provide bursaries to young women in Uganda   to attend secondary school. The grant and trust gave 75% of scholarships to girls and by 2007 and the trust had supported the education of 1,868 children.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.arcadiafund.org.uk/media/4980/2008.pdf|title=Arcadia Annual Review 2008|last=|first=|date=30 May 2019|website=Arcadia Annual Review 2008|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nArcadia has provided a total of $6 million in 2005\u201306  to the Human Rights Watch (US)  to help their empirical research into persecution of women, and its fact gathering, press releases, advocacy and lobbying .<ref name=\":2\" /> .<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Grant Statistics and Graphs ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n<u>Arcadia's Largest Grants ($USD)</u>\n!Recipient\n!Title of Grant\n!Date of Grant (D/M/Y)\n!Value ($USD)\n!Type Of Grant\n!Description of Grant\n|-\n|[[SOAS, University of London|School of Oriental and African Studies]]\n|Endangered Languages Documentation Programme\n|25/07/2002\n|33,851,813\n|Cultural\n|The Academic Programme to train linguists documenting endangered languages. \n|-\n|[[University of Cambridge]]\n|Cambridge Conservation Initiative:\u00a0 Endangered Landscapes Programme\n|30/01/2018\n|31,441,100\n|Environmental\n|To develop and support large-scale projects seeking to create habitats that are rich in biodiversity and resilient to environmental change.\n|-\n|[[Fauna and Flora International|Fauna & Flora International]]\n|Halcyon Programmes and core institutional support\n|01/10/2017\n|27,000,000\n|Environemental\n|To  expand the success of both the Halcyon Land & Sea Fund and the Halcyon Marine Programme to date, increasing focus on long-term sustainability.\n|-\n|Yale University\n|Institute for the Preservation of Cultural Heritage\n|01/06/2011\n|25,000,000\n|Cultural\n|To build a new cultural conservation and digitisation centre.\n|-\n|Yale University\n|The Hall of Graduate Studies\n|01/07/2017\n|25,000,000\n|Discretionary\n|To refurbish the Hall of Graduate Studies and to support the programmatic agenda that will transform it into a central home for the humanities at Yale\n|-\n|[[British Library]]\n|[[Endangered Archives Programme]]\n|27/01/2004\n|16,960,153\n|Cultural\n|To establish a  grants programme that funds projects that